<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIR ROBERT COCKBURN; SCIENTIST THWARTED NAZI RADAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sir Robert Cockburn, 85, British scientist who thwarted German radar during 
World War II, saving countless American and British planes and 
civilians.Educated at London University, Cockburn went into communications 
research for the Royal Aircraft Establishment at the outset of the war. He 
headed a group of scientists and engineers who devised a way to jam German 
navigational radio beams by releasing thin metallic foil strips into the air. 
The strips created a radar echo, making it impossible for German pilots to find 
their targets. After the war, Cockburn spent his career in government military 
research, primarily in atomic energy and guided missiles. Among his awards was 
the U.S. Congressional Medal for Merit. On March 21 in Aldershot, England. 
</P>
</TEXT>
