<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: VOTERS' OK SOUGHT FOR WELDON LANDFILL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOANNA M. MILLER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A San Diego County firm has filed a request to place a measure on the November 
ballot that would bypass county authorities by seeking voter approval for a 
landfill at Weldon Canyon, elections officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 In an unprecedented move, Taconic Resources filed its request late Tuesday to 
place the initiative on the ballot, said Bruce Bradley, assistant registrar of 
voters for Ventura County. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's never been done before with a land-use issue in Ventura County," Bradley 
said. "It's quite a unique effort." 
</P>
<P>
 If Taconic Resources is successful in obtaining 18,753 valid signatures by 
June 6, the measure would be placed on the general election ballot in November, 
Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
 The initiative will ask voters to amend the county's General Plan and 
applicable zoning ordinances to allow construction of a landfill and recycling 
center on 551 acres at Weldon Canyon, about three miles north of Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
 Waste Management Inc., which holds the lease to Weldon Canyon, withdrew its 
application for a land permit last summer after it became evident that the 
Board of Supervisors would defeat the measure. Taconic is now negotiating with 
Waste Management to take over the lease and would withdraw the initiative if no 
agreement is reached, said Richard Chase, Taconic general partner. 
</P>
<P>
 "I would expect us to have an agreement by this week," Chase said. "But you 
never know when a last-minute issue could arise." 
</P>
<P>
 Chase said he went forward with the filing to get the measure on the November 
ballot. Taconic figures it would take a year after voter approval to get other 
state, federal and local permits needed and six months to build the landfill 
after that. 
</P>
<P>
 The western county's largest dump, Bailard Landfill in Oxnard, is scheduled to 
close in 1997. JOANNA M. MILLER 
</P>
</TEXT>
