<HEADLINE>
<P>
OHIO STATE CONSIDERING AN OFFER TO PLAY IN PIGSKIN CLASSIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JASON H. REID 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After failing to lure Nebraska, organizers of the Disneyland Pigskin Classic 
have targeted Ohio State for the Aug. 29 college football game at Anaheim 
Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
 The Big Ten co-champion has been offered a spot to play Fresno State, but 
whether the Buckeyes accept is up to Coach John Cooper and the team, Athletic 
Director Jim Jones said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Don Andersen, executive director of the Orange County Sports Assn., which 
stages the game, is optimistic. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's not a done deal, but it's a definite possibility," Andersen said. "We've 
never had a Big Ten team . . . this would be a real plum for us." 
</P>
<P>
 Previously, Andersen believed he had an agreement with Nebraska Athletic 
Director Bill Byrne to have the Cornhuskers participate. But lack of team 
approval torpedoed the invitation. 
</P>
<P>
 Andersen said a commitment from Ohio State "would put that all behind us." He 
expects a decision within a few days. 
</P>
<P>
 "Ohio State has a great football tradition," Andersen said, "and the fact that 
they represent a market with a huge number of television homes is also a real 
plus." JASON H. REID 
</P>
</TEXT>
