<HEADLINE>
<P>
HUFFINGTON ATTACKS FEINSTEIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Santa Barbara Rep. Michael Huffington, a Republican candidate for U.S. Senate, 
launched a pair of commercials this week that attack Democratic incumbent 
Dianne Feinstein as being a big spender for supporting President Clinton's 
budget last year. The campaign did not disclose how much it paid for the ads, 
which are scheduled to air statewide for two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
 * THE ADS: One commercial charges that the 1993 budget's tax increases have 
hurt California's economy. "By a single vote, the Senate passed the biggest tax 
increase in American history -- that single vote is Dianne Feinstein's," the ad 
says. "Feinstein votes for the tax increase even though it hurts people on 
Social Security and small business. It costs Californians $27 billion." The 
second commercial seeks to contrast Huffington and Feinstein on fiscal issues. 
"Citizens Against Government Waste calls Huffington 'heroic.' The National 
Taxpayers Union ranks Feinstein the eighth-biggest spender -- ahead of even Ted 
Kennedy and Barbara Boxer." 
</P>
<P>
 * THE ANALYSIS: Huffington's campaign has two hopes for these ads -- that they 
will raise his still-obscure profile and check the popularity for Feinstein 
reflected in recent polls. Feinstein was listed eighth by the National 
Taxpayers Union, but the group acknowledges that its criteria could penalize 
prolific legislators. NTU says the government's cost for 31 bills co-sponsored 
by Feinstein last year was $42 billion, most due to her support for Clinton's 
failed jobs stimulus bill and his still-pending health care plan. Huffington, 
meanwhile, co-sponsored four spending bills last year that would save the 
government $19 billion. Still, he was the seventh-highest spender of 
California's 22 Republican House members. The commercial's reference to 
California's $27-billion cost for the 1993 budget is based on a study by the 
Heritage Foundation, a conservative think tank. Also, the 1993 tax package, one 
of the largest in history, targeted gas, wealthy households, businesses and 
upper-income Social Security recipients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
