779 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ZEDILLO GOES HOME AGAIN; MEXICO: PRI'S CANDIDATE KICKS OFF CAMPAIGN 
TRADITIONALLY: HE VISITS MEXICALI, THE TOWN WHERE HE GREW UP. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JUANITA DARLING, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ernesto Zedillo, the presidential candidate of Mexico's ruling party, launched 
his campaign Thursday with a Mexican political tradition: He visited his 
hometown, Mexicali. 
</P>
<P>
 But throughout his first day of persuading voters of his merits, Zedillo also 
confronted stark reminders that his will not be a traditional campaign. 
</P>
<P>
 Besides getting started barely four months before the Aug. 21 elections, the 
Zedillo campaign confronts dissension within his party and the long shadow of 
the assassination of his predecessor, Luis Donaldo Colosio. Colosio's March 23 
murder, which occurred as the candidate left a campaign rally in Tijuana, is 
still under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
 The morning before arriving in this border town, Zedillo left wreaths at 
Colosio's grave in the northern village of Magdalena de Kino and at the Tijuana 
assassination site, where he spent just eight minutes under intense security 
and made no public statements. 
</P>
<P>
 Later, he traveled to a luxury Tijuana hotel, where he met with local 
political leaders and a handful of newspaper editors. 
</P>
<P>
 That gathering site contrasted sharply with Zedillo's first stop in Mexicali, 
Colonia Pueblo Nuevo, a neighborhood of graffiti-covered single-story concrete 
houses where he lived as a child. 
</P>
<P>
 Dressed in an olive jacket and casual slacks, Zedillo occasionally reached 
through the circle of security guards to shake hands with onlookers as he 
walked along the unpaved street to his old home. Stepping into the front yard 
of the rambling house, with rooms of different materials and heights added by a 
series of owners, he spotted an electrical cable. 
</P>
<P>
 "I almost electrocuted myself there," he told the current inhabitants. 
</P>
<P>
 Later, before a crowd of about 1,500 in the municipal auditorium, Zedillo said 
that growing up in a working-class neighborhood taught him that "our most 
important commitment is to those who have the least." 
</P>
<P>
 Zedillo also told the cheering supporters: "You have taught me to believe that 
there is no challenge that cannot be overcome."  
</P>
<P>
 Earlier in the day, a prominent politician reminded Zedillo of one challenge 
he must confront. Outspoken Mexico City Councilman Demetrio Sodi made it clear 
that the candidate is facing a split in the Institutional Revolutionary Party, 
known as the PRI, that has ruled Mexico for 65 years. 
</P>
<P>
 The PRI's track record made Zedillo, 43, a Yale-educated economist, the 
automatic front-runner when he was named last week to replace Colosio. But that 
position has also made him an easy target of criticism from outside the party 
and dissent from within it. 
</P>
<P>
 Sodi, a 19-year PRI veteran, quit the party Thursday over Zedillo's 
nomination, which was essentially the unilateral choice of outgoing President 
Carlos Salinas de Gortari. 
</P>
<P>
 "I am resigning from the PRI because I am convinced that Ernesto Zedillo and 
his team will be incapable of carrying out the political and social reforms the 
country demands," Sodi said at a Mexico City news conference. "Zedillo is 
undoubtedly an intelligent and honorable man, but someone without political 
experience." 
</P>
<P>
 Other democracy-minded party activists, notably the Democracy 2000 movement, 
have also threatened to resign over the nomination, but Sodi is the first to 
actually do so. 
</P>
<P>
 Zedillo has responded indirectly to such threats by invoking the name of the 
slain candidate to call for party unity in speeches and in the few interviews 
he has granted. 
</P>
<P>
 The rally here included a moment of silence for Colosio, and Zedillo began his 
remarks by saying he is carrying on for his fallen friend. 
</P>
<P>
 But the frequent tributes to Colosio, victim of Mexico's most shocking 
political murder in 66 years, have begun to provoke criticism from opposition 
parties. The weekly magazine Proceso said in its latest issue that Zedillo 
remains in Colosio's shadow. 
</P>
<P>
 Concern about such criticism was the reason Zedillo excluded the reporters 
traveling with him from the grave and murder site visits, a campaign source 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Earlier in the week, Zedillo met at PRI headquarters with representatives of 
party factions, such as labor and farmers, who pledged their support. 
</P>
<P>
 This "buffalo stampede" is the traditional preamble to a PRI presidential 
campaign, followed by a trip to a town outside Mexico City that is linked to 
the candidate's childhood. 
</P>
<P>
 Zedillo was born in Mexico City, but moved to Mexicali as a small boy and 
lived here for several years before returning to the capital to study. 
</P>
<P>
 For the visit, the city has debuted Zedillo campaign billboards. Until 
Thursday, PRI advertising had been restricted to Colosio signs with freshly 
painted black ribbons. 
</P>
<P>
 Times staff writer Sebastian Rotella in Tijuana contributed to this report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
