<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: TORRANCE; DDT CLEANUP 
TO BEGIN IN 2 BACK YARDS NEXT WEEK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Crews will start work next Monday to remove DDT-contaminated soil from the 
yards behind two homes on West 204th Street near Torrance. 
</P>
<P>
 The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency says it will remove about 8,000 cubic 
feet of tainted soil from the two yards. At least two families will be 
relocated during the project, which is expected to take 10 days to two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
 Unusually high levels of the banned insecticide DDT were discovered in the 
back yards during federal testing last month. Although EPA officials say they 
do not know where the DDT came from, some residents believe it migrated from a 
nearby federal Superfund site, the former Montrose Chemical Corp. facility, 
where DDT was manufactured from 1947 to 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
