<HEADLINE>
<P>
POLICE ARREST DRIVER AFTER 3-CITY CHASE; CRIME: STOLEN CAR IS STOPPED AFTER 
TIRES ARE PUNCTURED. CAR MAY BE LINKED TO ROBBERIES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FERNANDO ROMERO, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A transient who led police on a chase through three Orange County cities was 
arrested after officers plastered a road with spikes to puncture his tires, 
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 The pursuit, which started just after midnight Thursday in Santa Ana, ended 
nearly 50 minutes later on a Huntington Beach street when the spikes worked, 
said Santa Ana police Lt. Robert Helton. 
</P>
<P>
 Arrested was Manuel Garcia Jr., 27, formerly of Fountain Valley but with no 
current address. 
</P>
<P>
 A female passenger was questioned and released. Garcia, who is on parole for 
burglary, is being held on suspicion of possession of a stolen car and evading 
arrest, Helton said. 
</P>
<P>
 Two Santa Ana police officers, who were slightly injured when their cruisers 
crashed during the chase, were treated at a local hospital, Helton said. Both 
patrol cars were heavily damaged. 
</P>
<P>
 The chase began at 12:32 a.m. in the 100 block of West Borchard Avenue when an 
officer did a computer check of a Ford Tempo that matched the description of a 
car used in recent robberies. The check revealed that the license plates on the 
car had been reported stolen March 8 in Costa Mesa, while the car itself had 
been stolen in Santa Ana, the lieutenant said. 
</P>
<P>
 The driver failed to stop, triggering a chase through Santa Ana, Fountain 
Valley and into Huntington Beach at speeds up to 50 m.p.h., he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Both of the car's front tires blew out at Springdale Street and Edinger Avenue 
after it ran over the spikes. Garcia drove the car several more blocks, 
stopping at Springdale Street and Warner Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
 Police, anticipating that the driver would head there, had stopped traffic in 
the immediate area before laying down the spikes to stop the car. 
</P>
<P>
 Investigators have yet to determine whether Garcia is linked to the robberies 
in which the Tempo was used. He will be arraigned today and then moved from 
City Jail to County Jail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA040894-0291 </DOCNO>
